  "base_commit": "b799510ebfc6538be6054e5764bdb50f9337a21c",
  "pr_number": 10291,
  "issue_number": 10266,
  "issue_title": "Paused query is not canceled after unmount when query not in cache",
  "issue_body": "### Describe the bug\n\nAccording to the query cancellation documentation, if `queryFn` consumes the abort signal then the query will be cancelled when it unmounts.\n\nHowever, if:\n\n- `signal` is consumed by `queryFn`\n- The query does not exist in the cache\n- The query's `networkMode` is `'online'`\n- The network is offline the entire time that the query is mounted\n\nIn this scenario, `queryFn` will be executed **with a non-aborted signal** when the network reconnects, even if it reconnects after the query has already unmounted. This behaviour does not depend on the value of `refetchOnReconnect`.\n\nThis behaviour does not happen if the query already exists in the cache (even if the query was cancelled and never successfully executed) which is why I classified it as a bug. I would not expect `queryFn` to be invoked with a non-aborted signal long after the component unmounts. \n\nThis behaviour could be problematic in a progressive web app or native app. If the device was offline for a while and the user was navigating between pages, then reconnecting to the network would cause many API requests to be sent all at once for queries that are no longer active.\n\n### Your minimal, reproducible example\n\nhttps://stackblitz.com/edit/vitejs-vite-6hwtvn5x?file=src%2Frepro.tsx\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. Ensure the query cache is empty, either by reloading the page or by clicking the \"Clear cache\" button.\n2. Set the network connection to \"offline\" in the browser's devtools.\n3. Click the \"Mount query\" button. Notice that the query appears as \"paused\" in the TanStack Query devtools.\n4. Click the \"Unmount query\" button. Notice that the query appears as \"inactive\" in the TanStack Query devtools.\n5. Set the network connection to \"online\"/\"no throttling\" in the browser's devtools.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n**Expected behaviour:** `queryFn` should not be invoked, or perhaps it should be invoked with an aborted signal.\n\n**Actual behaviour:** `queryFn` is invoked with a non-aborted signal. This is evidenced by the \"not aborted\" console logs in the browser's devtools as well as the TanStack Query devtools showing that the query is fetching.\n\n**Additional note:** You can observe that this behaviour does not occur when the query was previously executed and cancelled. After step 1, mount and unmount the query before the two second timeout finishes (while the network is online) then follow steps 2-5 as described above. The `queryFn` will not be invoked.\n\n### How often does this bug happen?\n\nEvery time\n\n### Screenshots or Videos\n\nhttps://github.com/user-attachments/assets/8a7b2ed7-20a5-4f5b-a807-970756e98a00\n\n### Platform\n\n- OS: macOS 15.7.4\n- Browser: Chrome 146.0.7680.76\n\n### Tanstack Query adapter\n\nreact-query\n\n### TanStack Query version\n\n5.90.21\n\n### TypeScript version\n\n5.9.3\n\n### Additional context\n\n_No response_",
